Observation Report for v3p0

Detailed observations and notes from the test run.

Observations

Vectors Feedback

QUIET, LOWVOL2

Significant noise leaks and artifacts (such as glitches and clicks) are present in both speech and non-speech regions.

low speech intelligibility and speech loss, where some letters are suppressed because the noise isn't completely eliminated.

Despite these issues, the overall signal quality and speech clarity are good.

LOWVOL3, LOWVOL4

Speech loss and distortion (where words are replaced with incorrect ones) are observed.

Noise leaks are also present in non-speech regions, often due to impulsive noise.

The output (OP) time domain waveform was saturated.

Despite these issues, the overall speech quality was good.

MIDVOL1, MIDVOL4

Issues include speech muffling (unclear words), speech distortion, noise artifacts (within speech regions), speech loss, and general noise leaks.

The major issues are noise leaks and noise artifacts.

Overall, the signal quality was moderate, and speech was degraded due to noise.

HIGHVOL1, HIGHVOL2

Speech loss, muffling, intelligibility issues, distortion, and noise leaks are present.

In some instances, noise was blended into the speech (i.e., noise inside the speech), resulting in a robotic voice sound.

Consequently, the overall quality of the speech was not good, with some vectors exhibiting degraded speech due to these issues.



MIDWIND, HIGHWIND

Midwind

Slight noise leakages, speech muffling, and speech distortion are present.

However, the overall speech quality was good.

Highwind

Significant speech loss (approximately 80% of speech is suppressed due to high wind) is observed.

A robotic voice is present in most vectors, and speaker originality changes are noticeable in some.

Other issues include speech distortion, low speech intelligibility, speech muffling, and noise leaks.

Overall, the quality of the signal was poor, and noise was not completely suppressed.


Major Areas to improve

Improve speech clarity and intelligibility.

Prevent speech loss (e.g., missing letters or words).

Avoid speech distortion and robotic effects.

Reduce muffling (unclear or low-volume speech).

Maintain the speaker’s natural voice (originality).

Handle wind noise and sudden background noises more effectively.

Observation Summary

HighVOL1, HighVOL2, HighWIND:

Major issues include speech loss and robotic voice quality

The model did not perform well under these noisy conditions.

MIDVOL1, MIDVOL2: Speech is not intelligible in some vectors and noise leaks

Observation Report for v3p0

Detailed observations and notes from the test run.

Observations

Vectors Feedback

QUIET, LOWVOL2

Significant noise leaks and artifacts (such as glitches and clicks) are present in both speech and non-speech regions.

low speech intelligibility and speech loss, where some letters are suppressed because the noise isn't completely eliminated.

Despite these issues, the overall signal quality and speech clarity are good.

LOWVOL3, LOWVOL4

Speech loss and distortion (where words are replaced with incorrect ones) are observed.

Noise leaks are also present in non-speech regions, often due to impulsive noise.

The output (OP) time domain waveform was saturated.

Despite these issues, the overall speech quality was good.

MIDVOL1, MIDVOL4

Issues include speech muffling (unclear words), speech distortion, noise artifacts (within speech regions), speech loss, and general noise leaks.

The major issues are noise leaks and noise artifacts.

Overall, the signal quality was moderate, and speech was degraded due to noise.

HIGHVOL1, HIGHVOL2

Speech loss, muffling, intelligibility issues, distortion, and noise leaks are present.

In some instances, noise was blended into the speech (i.e., noise inside the speech), resulting in a robotic voice sound.

Consequently, the overall quality of the speech was not good, with some vectors exhibiting degraded speech due to these issues.



MIDWIND, HIGHWIND

Midwind

Slight noise leakages, speech muffling, and speech distortion are present.

However, the overall speech quality was good.

Highwind

Significant speech loss (approximately 80% of speech is suppressed due to high wind) is observed.

A robotic voice is present in most vectors, and speaker originality changes are noticeable in some.

Other issues include speech distortion, low speech intelligibility, speech muffling, and noise leaks.

Overall, the quality of the signal was poor, and noise was not completely suppressed.


Major Areas to improve

Improve speech clarity and intelligibility.

Prevent speech loss (e.g., missing letters or words).

Avoid speech distortion and robotic effects.

Reduce muffling (unclear or low-volume speech).

Maintain the speaker’s natural voice (originality).

Handle wind noise and sudden background noises more effectively.

Observation Summary

HighVOL1, HighVOL2, HighWIND:

Major issues include speech loss and robotic voice quality

The model did not perform well under these noisy conditions.

MIDVOL1, MIDVOL2: Speech is not intelligible in some vectors and noise leaks

Observation Report for v3p0_all

Detailed observations and notes from the test run.

IR4 and IR5 Analysis Report

Config1


While the IR4 and IR5 models consistently outperform the Fastorer model in reducing noise leakage.

All three models struggle with particularly challenging noise environments, as seen in the "major" speech loss in the Jae-Boat-xpc test and moderate distortion in the Ali-SubwayStation_incoming subway

All three models perform similarly when it comes to preserving the core speech signal. They all show comparable levels of speech loss , distortion and intelligibility In fact, all three models had the same number of instances with "low" and "moderate" speech distortion.

When it comes to muffling, the Fastorer model had fewer files with low muffling compared to the IR4 and IR5 models.

Config2

The data shows that all three models, FF_fastorer(16k), FF_ir4_causalop(24k), and FF_ir5_interpreterop(24k), perform very similarly in their ability to manage noise and preserve speech quality.

All three models struggle with particularly challenging noise environments, as seen in the "moderate" speech loss in the Jae-Boat-xpc some what speech preserved compared to config1

Fastorer reduced noise leakage and muffling in some files compared to IR4 &IR5

(Ex:Ali-ChelseaMarket-XPC2_lowsnr_msf.wav , task7-HIGHVOL1-Largo-6ch_Chandan2_msf.wav, wind_bike_msf.wav )

IR4/IR5 Analysis (GVPMOS)

After comparing the subjective and objective results, that most files performed better with IR4, although some files did better with IR5.

There is no significant difference between the two models, but IR4 is slightly better than IR5.

In competing voice analysis, IR5 performed slightly better than IR4 and the difference isn't huge.

Observation Report for v3p0_all

Detailed observations and notes from the test run.

IR4 and IR5 Analysis Report

Config1


While the IR4 and IR5 models consistently outperform the Fastorer model in reducing noise leakage.

All three models struggle with particularly challenging noise environments, as seen in the "major" speech loss in the Jae-Boat-xpc test and moderate distortion in the Ali-SubwayStation_incoming subway

All three models perform similarly when it comes to preserving the core speech signal. They all show comparable levels of speech loss , distortion and intelligibility In fact, all three models had the same number of instances with "low" and "moderate" speech distortion.

When it comes to muffling, the Fastorer model had fewer files with low muffling compared to the IR4 and IR5 models.

Config2

The data shows that all three models, FF_fastorer(16k), FF_ir4_causalop(24k), and FF_ir5_interpreterop(24k), perform very similarly in their ability to manage noise and preserve speech quality.

All three models struggle with particularly challenging noise environments, as seen in the "moderate" speech loss in the Jae-Boat-xpc some what speech preserved compared to config1

Fastorer reduced noise leakage and muffling in some files compared to IR4 &IR5

(Ex:Ali-ChelseaMarket-XPC2_lowsnr_msf.wav , task7-HIGHVOL1-Largo-6ch_Chandan2_msf.wav, wind_bike_msf.wav )

IR4/IR5 Analysis (GVPMOS)

After comparing the subjective and objective results, that most files performed better with IR4, although some files did better with IR5.

There is no significant difference between the two models, but IR4 is slightly better than IR5.

In competing voice analysis, IR5 performed slightly better than IR4 and the difference isn't huge.

Observation Report for v3p0_sorted

Detailed observations and notes from the test run.

Observations

Vectors Feedback

QUIET, LOWVOL2

Significant noise leaks and artifacts (such as glitches and clicks) are present in both speech and non-speech regions.

low speech intelligibility and speech loss, where some letters are suppressed because the noise isn't completely eliminated.

Despite these issues, the overall signal quality and speech clarity are good.

LOWVOL3, LOWVOL4

Speech loss and distortion (where words are replaced with incorrect ones) are observed.

Noise leaks are also present in non-speech regions, often due to impulsive noise.

The output (OP) time domain waveform was saturated.

Despite these issues, the overall speech quality was good.

MIDVOL1, MIDVOL4

Issues include speech muffling (unclear words), speech distortion, noise artifacts (within speech regions), speech loss, and general noise leaks.

The major issues are noise leaks and noise artifacts.

Overall, the signal quality was moderate, and speech was degraded due to noise.

HIGHVOL1, HIGHVOL2

Speech loss, muffling, intelligibility issues, distortion, and noise leaks are present.

In some instances, noise was blended into the speech (i.e., noise inside the speech), resulting in a robotic voice sound.

Consequently, the overall quality of the speech was not good, with some vectors exhibiting degraded speech due to these issues.

MIDWIND, HIGHWIND

Midwind

Slight noise leakages, speech muffling, and speech distortion are present.

However, the overall speech quality was good.

Highwind

Significant speech loss (approximately 80% of speech is suppressed due to high wind) is observed.

A robotic voice is present in most vectors, and speaker originality changes are noticeable in some.

Other issues include speech distortion, low speech intelligibility, speech muffling, and noise leaks.

Overall, the quality of the signal was poor, and noise was not completely suppressed.

Major Areas to improve

Improve speech clarity and intelligibility.

Prevent speech loss (e.g., missing letters or words).

Avoid speech distortion and robotic effects.

Reduce muffling (unclear or low-volume speech).

Maintain the speaker’s natural voice (originality).

Handle wind noise and sudden background noises more effectively.

Observation Summary

HighVOL1, HighVOL2, HighWIND:

Major issues include speech loss and robotic voice quality

The model did not perform well under these noisy conditions.

MIDVOL1, MIDVOL2: Speech is not intelligible in some vectors and noise leaks

Observation Report for v3p0_sorted

Detailed observations and notes from the test run.

Observations

Vectors Feedback

QUIET, LOWVOL2

Significant noise leaks and artifacts (such as glitches and clicks) are present in both speech and non-speech regions.

low speech intelligibility and speech loss, where some letters are suppressed because the noise isn't completely eliminated.

Despite these issues, the overall signal quality and speech clarity are good.

LOWVOL3, LOWVOL4

Speech loss and distortion (where words are replaced with incorrect ones) are observed.

Noise leaks are also present in non-speech regions, often due to impulsive noise.

The output (OP) time domain waveform was saturated.

Despite these issues, the overall speech quality was good.

MIDVOL1, MIDVOL4

Issues include speech muffling (unclear words), speech distortion, noise artifacts (within speech regions), speech loss, and general noise leaks.

The major issues are noise leaks and noise artifacts.

Overall, the signal quality was moderate, and speech was degraded due to noise.

HIGHVOL1, HIGHVOL2

Speech loss, muffling, intelligibility issues, distortion, and noise leaks are present.

In some instances, noise was blended into the speech (i.e., noise inside the speech), resulting in a robotic voice sound.

Consequently, the overall quality of the speech was not good, with some vectors exhibiting degraded speech due to these issues.

MIDWIND, HIGHWIND

Midwind

Slight noise leakages, speech muffling, and speech distortion are present.

However, the overall speech quality was good.

Highwind

Significant speech loss (approximately 80% of speech is suppressed due to high wind) is observed.

A robotic voice is present in most vectors, and speaker originality changes are noticeable in some.

Other issues include speech distortion, low speech intelligibility, speech muffling, and noise leaks.

Overall, the quality of the signal was poor, and noise was not completely suppressed.

Major Areas to improve

Improve speech clarity and intelligibility.

Prevent speech loss (e.g., missing letters or words).

Avoid speech distortion and robotic effects.

Reduce muffling (unclear or low-volume speech).

Maintain the speaker’s natural voice (originality).

Handle wind noise and sudden background noises more effectively.

Observation Summary

HighVOL1, HighVOL2, HighWIND:

Major issues include speech loss and robotic voice quality

The model did not perform well under these noisy conditions.

MIDVOL1, MIDVOL2: Speech is not intelligible in some vectors and noise leaks
